Given the general system description: The user would like to build a system called lift_system, where Lift: 2-floor building, door opens 3 ticks. Lift moves 2 ticks when button pressed. Door and lift operate concurrently.. There are 3 processes in the system, the descriptions of the processes are as follows: Door: Door opens for 3 ticks then closes. Repeats.; LiftCar: Moves between floors in 2 ticks when button pressed.; Button: Button can be pressed anytime to call the lift., now generate the PAT code corresponding to the **following system annotation**. Refer to the system description **only** if explicitly guided in the annotation, or if there is a contradiction between the annotation and the description.

### System Annotation:
// "DOOR_OPEN": State value representing door open (set to 1)
// "DOOR_CLOSED": State value representing door closed (set to 0)
// "DOOR_OPEN_TICKS": Number of ticks door remains open before closing (set to 3)
// "FLOOR_0": Ground floor identifier (set to 0)
// "FLOOR_1": First floor identifier (set to 1)
// "LIFT_MOVE_TICKS": Number of ticks required to move between floors (set to 2)
// "BUTTON_NOT_PRESSED": State indicating button is not pressed (set to 0)
// "BUTTON_PRESSED": State indicating button has been pressed (set to 1)
// "doorState": Current state of the door (initial value is DOOR_CLOSED)
// "doorTimer": Ticks remaining before door changes state (initial value is 0)
// "currentFloor": Current floor of the lift car (initial value is FLOOR_0)
// "liftTimer": Ticks remaining during movement; 0 indicates idle (initial value is 0)
// "buttonState": Current state of the call button (initial value is BUTTON_NOT_PRESSED)
// === System Behavior (Timed) ===
// Lift: 2-floor building, door opens 3 ticks. Lift moves 2 ticks when button pressed. Door and lift operate concurrently.
// Process Door: Door opens for 3 ticks then closes. Repeats.
// Process LiftCar: Moves between floors in 2 ticks when button pressed.
// Process Button: Button can be pressed anytime to call the lift.
// Timing requirements:
// - door open lasts 3 time units
// - floor travel takes 2 time units


// define the lift_system system: overall system combining all the subsystems interleavingly ("|||"), consider defining the system around the most central variable (e.g., the number of owners) only if appropriate
// define **exactly** the following states and assertions as specified. Do **NOT** add, modify, or omit anything
// assert lift_system system deadlockfree
// define at_floor2: lift_floor = FLOOR2
// assert that the lift_system system can reach the state "at_floor2"

The PAT code should be:
### Response:

answerClaude:
#define DOOR_OPEN 1;
#define DOOR_CLOSED 0;
#define DOOR_OPEN_TICKS 3;
#define FLOOR_0 0;
#define FLOOR_1 1;
#define LIFT_MOVE_TICKS 2;
#define BUTTON_NOT_PRESSED 0;
#define BUTTON_PRESSED 1;

var doorState = 0;
var doorTimer = 0;
var currentFloor = 0;
var liftTimer = 0;
var buttonState = 0;

Door() = open_door{doorState = DOOR_OPEN;} -> Wait[DOOR_OPEN_TICKS]; close_door{doorState = DOOR_CLOSED;} -> Door();

LiftCar() = Idle();
Idle() = [buttonState == BUTTON_PRESSED] start_move{liftTimer = LIFT_MOVE_TICKS; buttonState = BUTTON_NOT_PRESSED; currentFloor = (currentFloor == FLOOR_0 ? FLOOR_1 : FLOOR_0);} -> Wait[LIFT_MOVE_TICKS]; arrived{liftTimer = 0;} -> Idle();

Button() = press{buttonState = BUTTON_PRESSED;} -> Button();

lift_system() = Door() ||| LiftCar() ||| Button();

#define at_floor2 currentFloor == FLOOR_1;

#assert lift_system deadlockfree;
#assert lift_system reaches at_floor2;

